<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06168109 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06168109 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: The M/S Southward will sail south to catch the solar eclipse onJuly 11  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  REPORT; DISEASE; SOUTH-AMERICA; RELATION; TO; TRAVEL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  STATE health officials say a recent epidemic of cholera in South America mayspread to California and are warning travelers to be careful of drinking waterand eating raw fish and unpeeled fruit.;    Dr. George Rutherford, chief ofthe infectious disease branch of the state department of health services, saidthe epidemic, which began in Peru in late January, marks the first majoroutbreak of cholera in the Western Hemisphere.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  STATE ISSUES CHOLERA WARNING TO TRAVELERS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Travelers' Advisory  </MEMO><TEXT>     Since then the potentially fatal disease has spread to Ecuador, Colombia,Brazil and Chile.;    About a dozen cases have appeared in New Jersey andFlorida, from people who were either in Peru or who ate foods brought backfrom there, Rutherford said. The bacteria associated with the disease aretransmitted principally through water and to a lesser extent through foodtainted by contaminated water, feces or soiled hands.;    &quot;We think it's quitelikely to spread into Central America and reach southern Mexico, which willundoubtedly result in cases in California,&quot; Rutherford said.;    He warnstravelers to be vigilant about all drinking water, including ice. Drinkbottled water, he advises.;    Raw or partially cooked fish and shellfish,especially ceviche, should be avoided, as well as raw or unpeeled vegetables.One safeguard is to make sure the food you eat is hot, he noted.;    And thecholera vaccine is ineffective, he added, &quot;so don't even bother getting it.&quot;;   He advised travelers returning from one of these areas suffering fromdiarrhea to see a doctor within a week and let the doctor know they've been ina cholera-infected area.;  Cruise news;  (box)  No room at the inn, said newsstories about travel opportunities to see the solar eclipse on July 11.Arrrrgh, said Melita W. Thorpe of Grouptrav National Inc. of Santa Cruz, whohas berths available on a cruise dedicated to the longest eclipse until theyear 2132.;    The M/S Southward will sail from Los Angeles July 8, headed forMazatlan, Cabo San Lucas and Ensenada. On July 11 the ship is expected to bein place for &quot;optimum viewing&quot; of the nearly seven-minute eclipse.;    Severalexperts will be aboard on the seven-day cruise to explain that Mr. Sun ishiding behind Mr. Moon.;    Fares start at $1,345 per person, based on doubleoccupancy. Information: (800) 877-3703.;    Other means of seeing the eclipsein Baja include:;    (box) Baja Expeditions had space in its beach camp twohours south of La Paz. Costs $1,195 per-person based on double occupancy in atent, July 10-14. Includes round-trip air fare from Los Angeles and transfersfrom La Paz. Phone (800) 843-6967.;    (box) Earth, Sea and Sky Tours, whichrents private villas and condominiums in southern Baja, had about eightrentals available as of last week. Call (800) 745-2226.;    (box) The MexicoConnection has a few spaces in Los Cabos, ranging from $800 to $1,300 perperson, double occupancy. The catch: departures are from Phoenix. Phone (800)521-4455.;  Say, are you gay?;  If you're interested in a very different, aswell as funny and informative, view of the Grand Tour of Europe, you may wantto check out &quot;Are You Two . . . Together? A Gay and Lesbian Travel Guide toEurope&quot; (Random House, $18). Authors Lindsy Van Gelder and Pamela Robin Brandtare making the rounds at local bookstores. This week you can catch them at:;   (check) 7 p.m. to 8:30 p.m., Monday, ClaireLight Books, 1110 Petaluma HillRoad No. 5, Santa Rosa.;    (check) 7 p.m. to 8:30 p.m., Tuesday, SisterspiritWomen's Bookstore, 175 Stockton Ave., San Jose.;    (check) 7 p.m. to 9 p.m.,Wednesday, Lioness Books, 2224 J Street, Sacramento.;    (check) 7 p.m. to8:30 p.m., Friday, Storyteller Bookstore, 16350 Third St., Guerneville.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News staff and wire report  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910616  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3T  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  638  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday June 16, 199100168109,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>